---
import LessonLayout from '../../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
---
<LessonLayout
  title="Computer Vision Basics"
  track="young-builders"
  week={7}
  phase="Phase 3: AI Projects"
  duration="60 min"
  emoji="👁️"
  objective="Use Reachy's camera to detect colors and shapes"
>
  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-builder-700 mb-3">🎯 Learning Objective</h2>
    <p class="bg-builder-50 border-l-4 border-builder-400 p-4 rounded-r-xl text-gray-700">
      You will understand how computers "see" images as pixel grids and numbers, implement basic color detection, and make Reachy react to visual input.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">📚 How Computers See</h2>
    <div class="bg-violet-50 border border-violet-200 rounded-xl p-5">
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">A camera image is just a grid of pixels. Each pixel is 3 numbers: (Red, Green, Blue) from 0-255.</p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-2 text-center text-xs font-mono">
        <div class="bg-red-400 text-white p-2 rounded">(255, 0, 0)<br/>Red</div>
        <div class="bg-green-500 text-white p-2 rounded">(0, 255, 0)<br/>Green</div>
        <div class="bg-blue-500 text-white p-2 rounded">(0, 0, 255)<br/>Blue</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">📋 Activity Steps</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-builder-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">1</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Pixel Art Activity (10 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">On graph paper, draw a 5×5 image using only R, G, B, W (red/green/blue/white) colours. Write the RGB value for each cell. This is exactly how a camera sees it!</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-builder-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">2</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Color Detector (30 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Run the code below. Add 3 new colors to detect. Make Reachy say the color name AND do a specific movement for each.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-builder-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">3</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Colour Game (10 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Hold up coloured objects. Can your colour detector identify them? What makes it fail? Why?</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-builder-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">4</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Reflect (10 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Write: what's the limitation of simple colour detection? What would make it smarter?</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">💻 Code Snippet</h2>
    <pre is:raw class="bg-gray-900 text-green-300 rounded-xl p-5 overflow-x-auto text-sm leading-relaxed"><code># vision.py — Week 7: Young Builders
import random
import time

# Simulated colour samples (R, G, B)
SAMPLE_COLOURS = {
    "red":    (220, 30, 30),
    "green":  (30, 200, 50),
    "blue":   (30, 60, 220),
    "yellow": (240, 220, 20),
    "white":  (240, 240, 240),
    "unknown": (128, 100, 90),
}

def classify_colour(r, g, b):
    """Classify RGB pixel as a named colour."""
    # Find the dominant channel
    max_val = max(r, g, b)

    if max_val < 60:
        return "black"
    if min(r, g, b) > 180:
        return "white"
    if r > g and r > b and r > 150:
        return "red"
    if g > r and g > b and g > 120:
        return "green"
    if b > r and b > g and b > 120:
        return "blue"
    if r > 180 and g > 180 and b < 80:
        return "yellow"

    return "unknown"

class ReachyMock:
    def say(self, msg): print(f"🔊 {msg}"); time.sleep(0.5)
    def set_emotion(self, e): print(f"😊 *{e}*"); time.sleep(0.3)
    def wave(self): print("👋 *waves*"); time.sleep(0.5)

try:
    from reachy_mini import ReachyMini
    robot = ReachyMini()
except Exception:
    robot = ReachyMock()

COLOUR_REACTIONS = {
    "red":    lambda: (robot.set_emotion("excited"), robot.say("Red! That's bold!")),
    "green":  lambda: (robot.set_emotion("happy"), robot.say("Green! Like nature!")),
    "blue":   lambda: (robot.set_emotion("curious"), robot.say("Blue! Like the sky!")),
    "yellow": lambda: (robot.wave(), robot.say("Yellow! So bright!")),
    "white":  lambda: (robot.set_emotion("neutral"), robot.say("White — clean and simple.")),
    "black":  lambda: (robot.set_emotion("neutral"), robot.say("Dark...")),
    "unknown": lambda: (robot.set_emotion("curious"), robot.say("Hmm, what colour is that?")),
}

print("🎨 Reachy Colour Vision Demo\n")
for colour_name, (r, g, b) in SAMPLE_COLOURS.items():
    detected = classify_colour(r, g, b)
    print(f"👁️  Pixel ({r}, {g}, {b}) → detected: {detected}")
    if detected in COLOUR_REACTIONS:
        COLOUR_REACTIONS[detected]()
    print()</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">💬 Reflection Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-4"><p class="font-semibold text-blue-800">💭 Why does lighting affect colour detection? How could you fix that?</p></div>
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-4"><p class="font-semibold text-blue-800">💭 How is this different from how a human recognizes colours?</p></div>
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-4"><p class="font-semibold text-blue-800">💭 What would you need to detect SHAPES instead of colours?</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">👪 Parent Tips</h2>
    <div class="bg-purple-50 border border-purple-200 rounded-xl p-5 text-gray-700">
      <p>💡 This is an intro to computer vision — the same tech behind facial recognition, self-driving cars, and medical imaging. Your child is touching one of AI's most important domains!</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</LessonLayout>
